Beginning September 1st, breakfast and lunch is FREE to all Powers Lake Public School Students. The USDA has granted a waiver extension for free meals until December 31st, 2020. This means ALL students in grades K-12 will receive free breakfasts and lunches until December 31st, 2020, regardless of their free/reduced status.

What you need to know:

You may continue to fill out free and reduced applications to ensure that your status will remain in January 2021. If you have already filled out an application and been considered reduced or denied, you will not be charged for meals until January 2021.

The free meal is intended to be a complete meal. Students wanting to purchase individual items, such as milk or an extra entree must pay a la carte prices.

Any money on your student’s account will remain until charges begin again on January 1st, 2021.

post_text:
Good evening. The staff of Powers Lake School is excited to get started next week. A couple things to fill you in on before next week.
1. Each student should have a fillable water bottle. We will have the filling stations turned on but not the regular drinking fountains.
2. We ask the all students have a face covering available. Masks, gators and face shields are all acceptable. Masks are not required except on the bus to start the year but there may be instances throughout the day when students may need one.
3. On the first day of school we are asking that parents do their best to remain outside the school. In order to come in, you will have to have your temperature taken and answer several question to assure you are healthy. We will allow parents of kindergarten students to drop their student off in the classroom. All other students being dropped off should be dropped off and enter through the West door.

Again we know that this may be an inconvenience, but we appreciate your cooperation and a positive attitude. Throughout this process our community can “adapt, and thrive!”

post_text:
Good morning. Here is some information about bussing to start off the school year. Our bus routes will run similar to last year. Each bus will need to have a seating chart and the students must sit in that seat before and after school. Only children from the same household will be allowed to sit together in one seat.

All students and drivers will be required to wear face coverings while on the bus. Drivers will take temperatures of students before they go to their seat. If the student has a fever of 100.4 or higher they will be required to stay home. We also ask that there be no snacks eaten on the bus in the morning or after school as well.

We will not be picking up town kids to start the year, and we will not be able to add kids to routes each day. If you have ridden the bus before and your situation has changed please contact the school and let us know.

We know that this may be an inconvenience for some of you but we appreciate your cooperation and look forward to having the students back in school.

The North Dakota Department of Public Instruction has partnered with the Governor’s Office, Forum Communications and Microsoft to produce a virtual Celebration for the North Dakota Class of 2020. This statewide celebration will honor graduates from every high school in North Dakota with a slideshow. Microsoft Teams will enable viewers to listen to guest speakers, including Governor Burgum, Carson Wentz, Josh Duhamel, and a performance by Tigerlily.

The North Dakota Class of 2020 Celebration can be viewed on May 30 at 2 p.m. Central/1 p.m. Mountain time by tuning in to your local ABC station (WDAY, WDAZ, KBMY and KMCY) or by visiting Inforum.com, GrandForksHerald.com, JamestownSun.com, TheDickinsonPress.com or WestFargoPioneer.com.

The livestreams will be featured at the top of each news site's homepage and will not require registration or subscription to watch.

Please use the following schedule next week to drop -off technology, clean out lockers/desks, etc. Parents will be allowed to come into the building to gather personal items from student lockers and desks. Please use the plastic bag that was provided to drop-off any technology. Pick-up times are staggered to allow for proper physical distancing as per ND Smart ReStart guidelines.

K/1st grade: 9am - 10am
2nd/ 3rd grade: 10am - 11am
4th/5th grade: 11am - 12pm
6th-12th grade: 12pm - 3pm
K-12th grade: 6pm - 7pm

Please use the bus lanes in the main parking lot as school staff will guide you at that point. Stay safe and finish strong.

Mr. Gruenberg

All K-12 instruction will end on Friday, May 15th. The week of May 18-21 will be making up missing/incomplete work, cleaning out lockers, and the returning of school materials: library books, textbooks, technology devices, and school supplies (scissors, markers, crayons, etc.). More detailed information about the week of May 18-21 and graduation will be provided soon. We are expecting guidance from ND DPI by the middle of this week.

Have a great week as finish strong!

Sincerely,

Powers Lake K-12 Staff

post_text: Couldn’t have said it any better, sister-in-law! Education comes in many forms!
shared_text:
Justine Gruenberg
April 21 at 7:45 PM ·

Posting this again. I needed this message today. It's ok. They'll be ok. If they’re (or I’m) not in a good mindset, let it be. Let them play. Let them choose one math and one reading activity, even if it's an app like Epic and Prodigy. Try again later, or try again tomorrow. Go out for a walk, play a game, bake a cake, or just sit down together in front of an educational (or not) cartoon with a couple of spoons and quart of ice cream. We’ll get through this. Our superheroes will be there when school starts again to help us all. ❤️ God bless teachers. 🙏🏼 (and my children, because they need it. 😂)

shared_text:
ND Department of Public Instruction
April 20 at 5:07 PM ·

Some information to consider as North Dakotans debate when, or whether, K-12 schools should reopen for the end of the 2019-20 school year. The Centers for Disease Control guidance on avoiding gatherings of more than 10 people is in effect until April 30, at least. Our number of reported COVID-19 infections has been rising sharply; Gov. Burgum has said the infection rate would need to be falling before he would consider lifting his school-closure executive order. The regularly scheduled end of the school year will arrive within five weeks from TODAY for more than two-thirds of North Dakota’s students; in other words, any school reopening for 2019-20 would be brief. Students and teachers alike are hitting a groove on the distance-learning practices that began statewide on April 1. ND State School Superintendent Kirsten Baesler discussed this information on WZFG-AM “The Flag” Radio Monday morning.

Powers Lake Community Club is hosting an Earth Day Trash Pick Up Challenge!

Help make Powers Lake look beautiful and celebrate Earth Day by cleaning up our community! To be a part of the challenge, go out and pick up as much trash as possible from around town or your road ditches around the Powers Lake area. Send a picture of the bags of trash you collected to 701-339-8416 to be entered for a chance to win! Think about all the public places that trash piles up... parks, around the lake, streets, empty lots, ball fields, etc!

Take advantage of the nice weather and extra time at home to help clean up our community!

The challenge will run from Tuesday, April 21st to Sunday, April 25th. Make sure you send your picture by Sunday night to enter the challenge!

Please share this post and spread the word!

As we move to distance learning for all students grades K-12, it is imperative that your students log into Seesaw for K-5 and Microsoft Teams, K12 email, and Edmodo for 6-12. As a school, we are required to keep track of your student's progress and attendance.

Teachers will make all attempts to contact their students using their online platform, email, text or phone call. If a teacher can not get a hold of a particular student, they will be marked absent for the day or the class period.

Powers Lake Public School will be joining in with other schools to turn on the stadium lights. We will be turning on the football stadium lights tonight, Friday April 3, from 7:00 to 9:30PM as a way to honor our students, staff, and community members in this time of distance learning while school buildings are closed due to COVID-19 concerns.

These lights are a symbol of hope and an assurance that our students are in our hearts and on our minds. As anyone sees the lights, be assured that we are still there for our community and our students. No matter the struggles, the Outlaw Family is in it together.

An update for tomorrow's material / technology pickup for all K-12 students:

Pickup will be from 9 am - 12 pm. Please only use the bus lane in the middle of the north parking lot. We will come out to your vehicle and give you your student's items that they will need. post_text:
FBLA State Leadership Conference
As of right now, there will be NO physical conference. As for students competing, that will still happen. The students have all of the information available to them in their school e-mail accounts.
They will NOT be required to meet physically. However, they can Facetime or Zoom each other in order to finish their group projects if they need to. The competition looks more like submitting videos of their presentations, or taking their tests online at home using a username and password that will be provided to them. They have a 5 day window opportunity to complete their tests.
Again, all of that information is available to them. If they do NOT wish to compete anymore, obviously they can take that option as well. This is strictly a voluntary.
However, as far as anyone knows right now, the National Leadership Conference is still on for the end of June, and a good portion of my students have already competed in their respective competitions. They may have already placed. Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions. ~Mrs. Helseth

post_text:
Information from yesterday's video conference from the ND Department of Health regarding the Coronavirus and guidelines to follow for K-12 schools and childcare programs. The quick version includes:

Staying home when sick, properly wash your hands, and routinely clean surfaces with proper cleaning products.

As a school, we have a daily rotation of sanitizing high-traffic area surfaces with bleach solution. High traffic areas include students desks, door handles, chair arms, locker handles, lunch tables, etc. Also, both bathrooms have Purell touchless hand sanitizers for students and staff to use. If you have any other questions or concerns, please direct your questions to John Gruenberg at Powers Lake Public School.
#takesavillage #rancherpride.
